In 1874, Grant replaced Richardson as Treasury Secretary with [[Benjamin H. Bristow]], a man known for his honesty,{{sfn|McFeely|1974|p=148}} who began a series of reforms in the department, including tightening up the detective force and firing the second-comptroller for inefficiency.{{sfnm|Brands|2012a|1pp=556–557|Kohn|2000|2p=417|Nevins|1929|3p=56}} Discovering that millions of gallons of whiskey escaped taxation,{{sfn|Brands|2012a|pp=556–557}} and having Grant's endorsement to act ("Let no guilty man escape"), Bristow in May 1875 struck down the [[Whiskey Ring]], seizing 32 installations, impounding documents, and arresting some 350 men while obtaining 176 indictments.{{sfnm|McFeely|1974|1p=156|Nevins|1929|2p=56|Smith|2001|3p=584}} These led to 110 convictions and $3,150,000 in tax dollars was restored to the Treasury.{{sfn|Kohn|2000|p=417}}{{sfn|Nevins|1929|p=56}} When Bristow's investigation implicated Babcock as part of the Whiskey Ring, Grant became defensive, believing Babcock was the innocent victim of a witch hunt.{{sfn|Smith|2001|p=591}} While denying immunity to minor Whiskey Ring conspirators, Grant worked to protect Babcock.{{sfn|Kohn|2000|p=417}} In 1876, a jury acquitted Babcock at a trial influenced by Grant's deposition in Babcock's favor.{{sfn|Smith|2001|pp=592–593}} After the trial, under public pressure, Grant dismissed Babcock from the White House.{{sfn|Smith|2001|pp=591–593}}{{efn|McFeely, writing in 1981, believed that Grant knew of Babcock's guilt, while Smith, in 2001, believed the evidence against Babcock was circumstantial at best.{{sfnm|McFeely|1981|1p=415|Smith|2001|2p=591}}}} Grant pardoned some Ring members after a few months in prison, and pardoned Ring founder John McDonald after 17 months in jail.{{sfn|Kohn|2000|p=417}}

[[File:Cover of Harper's Weekly Dec 7, 1872.jpg|thumb|Cartoonist [[Thomas Nast]] praises Grant for rejecting demands by Pennsylvania politicians to suspend civil service rules.]]

As the scandals increased, Congress, with the House now under Democratic control, began several investigations into corruption in the administration, the most notable of which dealt with [[trader post scandal|profiteering at western trading posts]] involving Secretary of War [[William W. Belknap]], which led to his resignation.{{sfnm|Brands|2012a|1pp=560–561|Donovan|2008|2p=104}} Congress also investigated and reprimanded Navy Secretary George M. Robeson in 1876 for receiving bribes.{{sfn|McFeely|1974|p=153}} Grant's [[United States Civil Service Commission|Civil Service Commission]] reforms had limited success, as some members of his cabinet implemented a merit system that increased the number of qualified candidates and relied less on Congressional patronage.{{sfnm|Smith|2001|1pp=589–590|Simon|2002|2p=250}} Delano, however, exempted his department from competitive examinations, and Congress refused to enact permanent Civil Service reform.{{sfn|Smith|2001|p=589}} [[Zachariah Chandler]], who succeeded Delano, made sweeping reforms in the entire Interior Department; Grant ordered Chandler to fire all corrupt clerks in the Bureau of Indian Affairs.{{sfnm|Simon|2002|1p=250|Patrick|1968|2p=172}} In 1875, Grant fired Attorney General [[George Henry Williams]] after his wife was discovered to be involved in a bribery scandal, and appointed reformer [[Edwards Pierrepont]] in his place.{{sfn|White|2016|p=557}} Bristow and Pierrepont teamed up and became Grant's executive anti-corruption team. {{sfn|White|2016|p=557}} Postmaster [[Marshall Jewell]] using the postal department supported Bristow's investigations into the Whiskey Ring. {{sfnm|Smith|2001|1pp=584–585|Hesseltine|1957||2p=366}} Pierrepont cleaned up corruption among the [[United States Attorney]]s and Marshals in the South.{{sfn|Hesseltine|1957|p=374}} Grant suggested other reforms as well, including a proposal that states should offer free [[State school|public schooling]] to all children; he also endorsed the [[Blaine Amendment]], which would have forbidden government aid to schools with religious affiliations.{{sfn|Smith|2001|pp=570–571}} In November 1876, Grant apologized to the nation and admitted mistakes in his administration, saying, "[f]ailures have been errors of judgement, not of intent."{{sfn|McFeely|1981|pp=441–442}}

===Election of 1876===
{{main article|United States presidential election, 1876}}
Even as Grant drew cheers at the opening of the [[Centennial Exposition]] in May 1876, the collected scandals of his presidency, the country's weak economy, and the Democratic gains in the House led many in the Republican party to repudiate him in June.{{sfnm|McFeely|1981|1pp=440–441|Patrick|1968|2p=255}} Bristow was among the leading candidates to replace him, suggesting that a large faction desired an end to "[[Grantism]]" and feared that Grant would run for a third term.{{sfn|McFeely|1981|pp=440–441}} Ultimately, Grant declined to run, but Bristow also failed to capture the nomination, as the convention settled on Governor [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] of Ohio, a reformer.{{sfn|Smith|2001|pp=586, 596}} The Democrats nominated Governor [[Samuel J. Tilden]] of New York.{{sfn|Smith|2001|p=597}} Voting irregularities in three Southern states caused the election that year to remain undecided for several months.{{sfn|Smith|2001|p=598}} Grant told Congress to settle the matter through legislation and assured both sides that he would not use the army to force a result, except to curb violence.{{sfn|Smith|2001|pp=601–603}} On January 29, 1877, Grant signed legislation passed by Congress to form an [[Electoral Commission (United States)|Electoral Commission]] to decide the matter.{{sfn|Smith|2001|p=602}} The result was the [[Compromise of 1877]]: the Electoral Commission ruled that the disputed votes belonged to Hayes, but the last troops were withdrawn from Southern capitals.{{sfn|Smith|2001|p=604}} The Republicans had won, but Reconstruction was over.{{sfn|Smith|2001|p=604}} According to biographer Jean Edward Smith, "Grant's calm visage in the White House reassured the nation."{{sfn|Smith|2001|p=603}}

